splash: rebuild for seamless cold-start handoff (1.5s, no flicker)

Strict-review pass on the splash flow flagged seven concrete issues
beyond the cosmetic "two splashes" bug we fixed last commit:

  1. Total visible time was ~3.1 s (1800 hold + 700 reverse + 600
     route fade) — almost 2× the industry ceiling of 1.8 s.
  2. ``FlutterNativeSplash.preserve`` / ``.remove`` were never wired,
     so Flutter dropped the native splash on the *first* rendered
     frame regardless of whether SplashPage had decoded its bitmap
     — visible 1-frame orange flash on slower devices.
  3. ``Image.asset`` was decoded async with no ``precacheImage``, so
     the very first paint could be a logo-less orange screen.
  4. ``Opacity`` + ``Transform.scale`` inside an ``AnimatedBuilder``
     forced ``saveLayer()`` and an Image rebuild on every animation
     tick — pure overhead.
  5. No ``cacheWidth`` on ``Image.asset`` — Flutter allocated the
     full source bitmap (~1024×1024 RGBA = 4 MB) regardless of the
     device's actual screen width.
  6. ``Future.delayed`` callback was non-cancellable; if the splash
     was disposed during a config change or deep-link push, the
     closure still fired into a dead state.
  7. ``color_dark: "#14100C"`` flashed near-black before the orange
     Dart splash painted on dark-mode cold start.
  8. ``pushReplacement`` to AuthGate left a route the user could
     theoretically pop back to via ``Navigator.popUntil((r) =>
     r.isFirst)`` from elsewhere in the app.

Fixes
─────
* lib/pages/splash_page.dart — rewritten:
    - ``FadeTransition`` + ``ScaleTransition`` (no saveLayer, no
      per-frame Image rebuild).
    - ``precacheImage`` in ``didChangeDependencies``; only after it
      resolves do we ``FlutterNativeSplash.remove()`` and start the
      hold timer — guarantees the first visible Dart frame already
      has the bitmap cached.
    - Cancellable ``Timer`` (stored, killed in ``dispose``).
    - ``cacheWidth`` clamped to ``screenWidth × DPR`` (max 2048).
    - ``RepaintBoundary`` isolates the animated subtree.
    - Hand-off is a ``VoidCallback`` (``onComplete``), not a
      ``Navigator.pushReplacement`` — splash never enters the back
      stack.
    - Total visible time: 300 ms fade-in + 900 ms hold = ~1.2 s,
      then ~300 ms cross-fade to AuthGate via the parent's
      AnimatedSwitcher.  Down from 3.1 s.
    - Scale tween bumped from 0.96→1.0 (+4%, barely visible) to
      0.94→1.0 — still subtle, now actually perceptible.

* lib/main.dart
    - ``FlutterNativeSplash.preserve(widgetsBinding: binding)`` at
      the top of ``main()`` so the native surface stays up through
      Firebase init and ``appSettings.load()``.
    - New private ``_RootSwitcher`` widget at ``MaterialApp.home``:
      cross-fades between SplashPage and AuthGate via
      ``AnimatedSwitcher`` (300 ms, easeOut/easeIn cubic).  No
      navigator routing involved — splash is unreachable once
      dismissed.

* pubspec.yaml — ``flutter_native_splash``:
    - ``color_dark`` set to ``#FF6B35`` (was ``#14100C``).  Splash
      is brand identity and must look identical in light & dark;
      no more dark-mode flash.
    - Updated comments to document the colour-sync invariant
      between pubspec and ``AppColors.primary``.
    - Re-ran ``dart run flutter_native_splash:create`` so all
      Android drawable XMLs and the iOS launch storyboard
      regenerated with the new dark colour.

Verification
────────────
* ``flutter analyze`` — No issues found.
* Splash uses the existing ``AppColors.primary`` constant (already
  ``#FF6B35``) — no duplicate brand-colour declarations.
* Native splash + Dart splash now paint the *exact same* hex on
  both light and dark cold start.
